    @progfan234

    fa 3 hores (editat)
    ~5:03, as an Indian, I think I understand the psychology behind this. It's not exactly fake-it-till-you-make-it, but rather an urban Indian tendency/philosophy called "jugaad". The Google definition is somewhat flattering, but the closest translation is actually to the term "hacking" in a negative connotation. It centres around short-term thinking, a complete lack of interest in making things work long-term, with the primary focus being on getting through the day-to-day. In India, this applies not only to tech, but also to harder disciplines like building roads, administration, politics, reacting with religious fervour, etc. I have not noticed a tendency for this sort of "innovativeness" among other groups, which I think is why every such incident seems to involve Indians. I would suspect other cultures are not necessarily above or below this. Broad basic English proficiency and decades old recruitment infrastructure has made India the most fertile ground for this sort of labour. This is not different from why China produces the world's goods and you distrust the quality of their products.
